[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'ve seen digital picture frames before, but now there\'s something way better. Color e- paper, or some people call it e- in. And I don\'t just have one, but three. And one of them is the only one that exists in North America'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right now. Yeah, the engineers basically sent me the prototype. Crazy. Okay, so what\'s my beef with digital picture frames? Obviously, I like displaying pictures of our family or places we\'ve'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'traveled, but it\'s still a bright LED screen in the room, and I already have tons of bright LED screens in my life between my phone, iPad, and laptop. So, that\'s why I love e-aper displays. You know, the type of display that the'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Kindle uses. They\'re so much more pleasant to look at, and the battery life is significantly better since you only need to use the battery when changing the screen if it doesn\'t have a lightup display. So, with devices like'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these e-aper picture frames, you can hang them on the wall without any power cord attached. And it could be months or even years before you need to charge it again. Pretty sweet. All right, let\'s quickly go over these three e-aper'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'picture frames. And in some ways, they\'re similar, but in other ways, they\'re very different. The first one is the reflection frame. It\'s the most simple out of the three, which you may or may not like. To add pictures, I open'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up the reflection frame app to select a picture for my phone. Then tap the bottom left corner with the phone and that\'s it. Using NFC, it makes a connection and uses Bluetooth to'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transfer the image to the picture frame. Like I said, it\'s simple. No Wi-Fi, no cloud. But there are some tradeoffs. Anytime you want to change the picture, you have to pull out your phone and select one. You can\'t load multiple on'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at once. And with no Wi-Fi, you can\'t remotely add pictures. That\'s where these next two e-aper picture frames come in. E-aper picture frame. Yeah, that\'s a tongue twister. One is from'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Ara. They\'re a popular digital picture frame company, and this is their first e-paper version. They have a completely different approach from the reflection frame, which I just showed you. The Aura connects with Wi-Fi, and all the'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pictures are added using the cloud. So, to add a picture, I select one or multiple from my phone and add it to the Aura app, which syncs those images to the cloud. Then I can choose if I want the pictures to change every day,'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multiple times a day, or just stay the same. This makes it way more convenient to regularly change out the pictures and makes it really easy to add pictures remotely using the cloud. So, if you want to add pictures to a parent or'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'grandparents picture frame, it\'s no problem. You might be wondering if there\'s any subscription fees with this, and luckily there\'s not. Aura says you can add unlimited amount of photos, and there\'s no hidden costs or subscription fees, so that\'s great. There\'s also one'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'huge difference between this and the others that I\'ll get to in a second when comparing some of the extra features. And the last e-aper picture frame is from Switchbot. You know that prototype that I was mentioning earlier. This one'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of sits between the first two and how it functions. So instead of using the cloud, I can add pictures using the SwitchBot app directly to the picture frame, but unlike the reflection frame, I can store 10 images on the picture'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame and they can rotate on a schedule. I like that the pictures can rotate on a schedule, but there are some massive differences when you look closer at all three of these. Some of them might be a deal breakaker for you. For example, not'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only do these e-aper displays look like picture frames, some actually are. The reflection frame offers different frame colors, but it doesn\'t seem like it can be changed later. The SwitchBot e-aper frame, on the other hand, is compatible'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the IKEA rolome frames. You can just buy a very inexpensive IKEA frame and swap it out. That\'s pretty sweet. The SwitchBot picture frame is also allegedly going to work with Home Assistant, so you\'ll be able to use Home'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Assistant to swap out the images. And since I use Home Assistant to run my smart home, it\'s no surprise I\'m a huge fan of that. But there\'s one feature on this that I might not be a huge fan of, AI art that I have to pay a subscription'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for. I don\'t know, call me old school, but I prefer to see pictures of my family. I guess someone could be married to AI and this is how they show their love. Hey, no judgments here. And to be fair, it can give life to old pictures,'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is kind of cool. Ara can\'t change out the frame, but is significantly smaller than the other frames. Even though the image is the same size, the overall width, height, and depth of the'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame are smaller. But the biggest difference is that the Aura has a front light that can light up the picture. There\'s an ambient light sensor that can change the brightness to match the lighting in the room and it helps the image pop more and does make a big'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'difference. When I asked my family which picture they like the best, they all chose Aura and I think it\'s because of the light. It really helps fix some of the drawbacks with color e-aper displays. Obviously, a light is going to'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have a major drain on battery life, but there is a motion sensor on board to only use the light if someone is nearby, and it can be disabled by limiting the schedule of when it can turn on. The biggest difference between all three of'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these is how accurate the image is. The reflection frame is the most accurate out of the three. The colors look very close to the original image on my phone, and there are no weird color blotches. The aura is a close second, but it'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doesn\'t seem to show the color yellow very well. Look at the difference between these two pictures. The reflection frame shows a yellow in the light and a yellow cones at the bottom. The aura picture is displaying those as'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'almost white. When looking up at the steam cloud or whatever that is, the aura image looks a little blotchy compared with the reflection frame that has those colors blending in in a more natural looking way. Not a huge deal,'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but just something to be aware of. The SwitchBot frame is the least natural looking out of the three. I know this is kind of in beta, but they\'re boosting the saturation and contrast off the charts. They\'re going for like an oil'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'painting look or something. Seriously, what is this? Uh, Instagram filter from 2012. They do allow some image adjustments when saving a picture to the frame where I can lower the saturation and contrast all the way. Even then, the'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image still doesn\'t look as natural as the others. But they\'re working on improving it since, like I said, this is a prototype. So, with all things considered, what is my favorite? Well, if I were buying one of these as a gift,'

[06:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I would choose the Aura. It\'s the easiest to add a bunch of pictures and would be perfect to give to a parent. That way, they can see lots of pictures of their grandkids and you can add them even if you live far away. Ara also feels the most premium out of the three,'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it should because it is expensive. It\'s $500, which is very pricey. I know that price might be a definite no for some, but for others, it might be still worth it, especially if you\'re buying it'

[06:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for a parent and you\'re going in with a bunch of siblings to split the cost. It could be a really nice gift and it\'s available now. You would think that the SwitchBot would be my favorite because it will work with Home Assistant, but I can\'t get over how the image looks. It\'s'

[07:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still being developed, so Switchbot could make some adjustments. It does cost less at $350, but I recognize that\'s still not cheap. The reflection frame is also $350 bucks, and if I were buying one for myself right now, I would'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'probably go with this one. The image looks the best, and even though I have to manually swap out the pictures, it\'s very easy to do. It\'s also available now, and I\'ll have links to everything down below. I\'m sure there\'s comments'

